> The accuracy scoring weight at 95%. However, the proving time weight is still 0%, and the proof size weight is still 5%. Will there be no adjustments to these weight ratios in the future?
There may be adjustments made here yes, these fields are intentionally configurable. We have a PR which will be merged shortly to adjust the MAE calculations to allow for increased accuracy over the current 98% (see here https://github.com/inference-labs-inc/omron-subnet/pull/108), this will allow for miners to get accuracy even more precise but is just a scale factor so existing rankings are unchanged. Once loss is very close, we expect to increase weights for proving speed and size to incentivize improved efficiency of the already-accurate circuits.

> How much memory is needed to circuitize the model?
This is up to the miner. Taking the ONNX and circuitizing directly will likely lead to OOM errors unless done on a significant machine, even then it's unlikely that the circuit will prove on a validator due to the immense size. The purpose of the competition is to provide as much freedom as possible to miners. Anything can be attempted to improve the accuracy and speed of the circuit. As long as the validator can benchmark the circuit, it will be compared with the ONNX for accuracy and evaluated (regardless of how the circuit is designed).

Hey @momos6210, great question! This feature is named Proof of Weights - where validators prove they’re accurately scoring miners, enabling trustless verification that everyone’s operating faithfully. Active validators in SN2 generate zero knowledge proofs of all incentive calculations, and we've been running several other subnets' incentive mechanisms for benchmarking purposes for months successfully. The core discussions around Proof of Weights, including our active exploration of a deeper, chain-level integration is live in the `proof-of-weights` channel in the Church of Rao here https://discord.gg/4aHEVxVZMz. 
You can find all relevant SN2 resources and guides, including how to implement custom ZK circuits and detailed information on Proof of Weights, here:
Guidelines for adding circuits to SN2: https://github.com/inference-labs-inc/omron-subnet/blob/main/docs/custom_circuit_integrations.md
General SN2 & Proof of Weights Documentation: https://docs.omron.ai
BIT Proposal: https://github.com/opentensor/bits/pull/10
Thanks. What's holding up the implementation of proof of weights?

can you explain this concept of bond resets? or provide like documentation on how this works

Yes absolutely. Validators accumulate bonds with miners as they "discover" them and add weights. With bonds reset, miners trigger their bonds to be reset down to zero, breaking the established bond between all validators and itself and allowing validators to "rediscover" their miner during the next epoch. We use this strategically with Yuma3 to reward honest validators for quickly discovering miners within the subnet while weight copying validators will theoretically lag in their discovery process by one epoch due to commit reveal. Since bonds effect dividends, the end result should be that weight copiers lag honest validation, resulting in larger stake weight to valuable validation within the subnet.
